<h1 id="using-radio">Using radio</h1>

<p>Radio enables users to select just one input at a time from a selection of inputs, for examples a yes or no answer.</p>

<p>If you want users to select multiple inputs at a time, use the <a href="checkbox">checkbox element</a></p>

<p>Radio is often used as part of a <a href="form">form</a></p>

<p><em>Note: Be sure to update all label and input attributes with the correct details i.e.</em></p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>&lt;label for=""&gt;
&lt;input id=""&gt;
&lt;input type=""&gt;
&lt;input name=""&gt;
&lt;input value=""&gt;
</code></pre></div></div>

<h2 id="how-to-use-radios">How to use radios</h2>

<p>Always position radios to the left of their labels. This makes them easier to find, especially for users of screen magnifiers.</p>

<p>Unlike with checkboxes, users can only select one option from a list of radios. Do not assume that users will know how many options they can select based on the visual difference between radios and checkboxes alone.</p>

<p>If needed, add a hint explaining this, for example, â€˜Select one optionâ€™.</p>

<p>You should arrange options alphabetically, unless thereâ€™s a clear need to arrange by use. You shouldnâ€™t pre-select an option, as users may miss the question.</p>

<h2 id="stacking">Stacking</h2>

<p>If there are only 2 options, itâ€™s fine to have them laid out horizontally. If there are more, they should be stacked vertically. Try to avoid having too many options. More than 5 or 6 and users could get confused or miss options. If necessary, use a series of simpler questions.</p>
